Calculating distance between neigbouring points¶

In [ ]:
# The euclidean distance and manhattan distance are implemented using the formalae
# the code is implemented using inporation for articles reference in the document below 
# Calculating the euclidean distance 
def euclidean_distance(ref_point, d_value):
    euc_distance = np.sqrt(np.sum((ref_point - d_value) ** 2))
    return euc_distance

# Calculating the manhatten distance 
def manhattan_distance(ref_point, d_value):
    distance = 0
    for r,d in zip(ref_point,d_value):
        distance += abs(r - d)
    return distance

Predicting using both Manhattan and Euclidean Distance¶

In [ ]:
# creating two functions one for manhattan and one for euclidean for further comparison
def euc_knn_predict(X_train, y_train, x_test, k=3):
    # going thorugh all x train values and calculating the difference to find out multiple classes 
    ref_distances = [euclidean_distance(x_test, x_train) for x_train in X_train]
    # sort and find the neighbours 
    k_neighbors_indices = np.argsort(ref_distances)[:k]
    
    k_neighbor_labels = [y_train[i] for i in k_neighbors_indices]

    # Voting to find the most common class label
    most_common = np.bincount(k_neighbor_labels).argmax()

    return most_common

def man_knn_predict(X_train, y_train, x_test, k=3):
    distances = [manhattan_distance(x_test, x_train) for x_train in X_train]
    k_neighbors_indices = np.argsort(distances)[:k]
    k_neighbor_labels = [y_train[i] for i in k_neighbors_indices]

    # Voting to find the most common class label
    most_common = np.bincount(k_neighbor_labels).argmax()

    return most_common

Using the KNN Function¶

Accuracy¶

In [ ]:
#  The code for calculating accuracy is inspired and implemented using the coursera lab 2.601 and sources referenced below 
def calculate_accuracy(y_test, y_pred):
    correct_predictions = np.sum(y_test == y_pred)
    total_predictions = len(y_test)
    accuracy = correct_predictions / total_predictions
    return accuracy

Confusion Matrix¶

In [ ]:
#  The code for calculating confusion matirx is inspired and implemented using the coursera lab 2.601 and sources referenced below 
def calculate_confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, num_classes):
    confusion_matrix = np.zeros((num_classes, num_classes), dtype=int)
    for true_label, predicted_label in zip(y_test, y_pred):
        confusion_matrix[true_label, predicted_label] += 1
    return confusion_matrix

Precision¶

In [ ]:
#  The code for calculating precision is inspired and implemented using the coursera lab 2.601 and sources referenced below 
def calculate_precision(confusion_matrix):
    num_classes = confusion_matrix.shape[0]
    precision = np.zeros(num_classes)

    for i in range(num_classes):
        true_positive = confusion_matrix[i, i]
        false_positive = np.sum(confusion_matrix[:, i]) - true_positive
        
        precision[i] = true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive) if (true_positive + false_positive) != 0 else 0

    return precision

Recall¶

In [ ]:
#  The code for calculating recall is inspired and implemented using the coursera lab 2.601 

def calculate_recall(confusion_matrix):
    num_classes = confusion_matrix.shape[0]
    recall = np.zeros(num_classes)

    for i in range(num_classes):
        true_positive = confusion_matrix[i, i]
        false_negative = np.sum(confusion_matrix[i, :]) - true_positive
        recall[i] = true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative) if (true_positive + false_negative) != 0 else 0

    return recall

F1 Score¶

In [ ]:
#  The code for calculating F!-score is inspired and implemented using the coursera lab 2.601 and sources referenced below 

def calculate_f1_score(confusion_matrix, precision, recall):
    num_classes = confusion_matrix.shape[0]
    f1_score = np.zeros(num_classes)

    for i in range(num_classes):
        f1_score[i] = 2 * (precision[i] * recall[i]) / (precision[i] + recall[i]) if (precision[i] + recall[i]) != 0 else 0

    return f1_score

Creating Function for KNN Implementation¶

In [ ]:
def print_knn(y_test, y_pred, target):
    # Convert the target variables to integers
    y_test_int = y_test.astype(int)
    unique_classes = len(np.unique(target))

    # Evaluate the classifier using the functions created above 
    conf_matrix = calculate_confusion_matrix(y_test_int, y_pred, unique_classes)
    precision = calculate_precision(conf_matrix)
    recall = calculate_recall(conf_matrix)
    f1_score = calculate_f1_score(conf_matrix,precision,recall)
    accuracy = calculate_accuracy(y_test, y_pred)
    
    #  converting the results into dataframes
    conf_matrix_df = pd.DataFrame(conf_matrix)
    precision_df = pd.DataFrame(precision)
    recall_df = pd.DataFrame(recall)
    f1_score_df = pd.DataFrame(f1_score)
    accuracy_df = pd.DataFrame([accuracy])
    
    # concatinate the df to create one df for returning a report of the results 
    knn_result = [precision_df,recall_df,f1_score_df, accuracy_df, conf_matrix_df]
    col_names = ['Precision', 'Recall', 'F1-Score','Accuracy', 'Confusion Matrix']
    analyse_df = pd.concat(knn_result,keys=col_names, axis=1)
    
    
    return analyse_df
